hands_on_practices.problem:
In a simplified model of tissue homeostasis, a population of cells is composed of two types: progenitor cells (P) and terminally differentiated cells (D). The population dynamics from one day to the next can be described by a linear transformation. Let the state of the system on day $k$ be represented by the vector $\mathbf{v}_k = \begin{pmatrix} P_k \\ D_k \end{pmatrix}$, where $P_k$ and $D_k$ are the populations of progenitor and differentiated cells, respectively.

The state on the next day, $\mathbf{v}_{k+1}$, is determined by the matrix equation $\mathbf{v}_{k+1} = M \mathbf{v}_k$, where $M$ is the transition matrix:
$$
M = \begin{pmatrix} 1.1 & 0.1 \\ 0.4 & 0.8 \end{pmatrix}
$$
The entries of $M$ represent the following processes:
- $M_{11} = 1.1$: Each progenitor cell contributes, on average, 1.1 progenitor cells to the next generation through self-renewal.
- $M_{12} = 0.1$: Each differentiated cell contributes, on average, 0.1 progenitor cells through de-differentiation.
- $M_{21} = 0.4$: Each progenitor cell contributes, on average, 0.4 differentiated cells through differentiation.
- $M_{22} = 0.8$: The survival rate of differentiated cells from one day to the next is 80%.

The long-term growth or decay of the cell populations is determined by the eigenvalues of the matrix $M$. An eigenvalue greater than 1 indicates a growing population mode. What are the eigenvalues of the transition matrix $M$?

A. {1.2, 0.7}

B. {1.1, 0.8}

C. {1.9, 0.84}

D. {-0.7, -1.2}

E. {1.0, 0.9}
